Walking home from cooking class each Sunday afternoon, I get to pass by one of the most beautiful churches in Merida, San Sebasti√°n. The arched colonnade behind it is a former barracks, and now houses a government office. The backdrop of sky is always stunning against the stone and white paint of the domed tower, whether it is the clearest blue or bursting with clouds like today. 
.
.
In the park at the front of the church, is it now allowed to sit on the benches. There are usually a few people there, each alone, sometimes a municipal worker sweeping or landscaping. It is very still and quiet. It's peaceful, but sad. It makes me think of a story @followmeyucatan told me about this neighborhood (and maybe he will chime in with some details I'm forgetting). He told me, during his historical tour that I enjoyed so much, that Barrio San Sebasti√°n was believed by the Spanish to be haunted. There were said to be underground caves that the Maya would hide in, and the sounds of their hidden voices from the caves sounded like ghosts. 
.
.
So I think about that sometimes when I pass by this neighborhood gathering place, now so silent that maybe we can hear ghosts. The absence is felt. A normal afternoon would bring families with children to play at the playground, pick-up f√∫tbol players, a group of teens practicing marching band drills, couples sitting and enjoying the breeze, the odd cart selling marquesitas or granizados. 
I miss them. I miss that. 
.
.

Ordos Kangbashi, China, is the world's largest ghost city.
Located in Inner Mongolia, Ordos Kangbashi was built to be a modern city with state of the art architecture, large stadiums, and gorgeous public spaces. The city achieved all that in just under 10 years, but failed to attract people.
It was built to house 300.000 people, but only 70.000 people moved into the city. Eventually, those people started to trickle out as well. The city stopped building and went bankrupt. Today, it is largely a ghost town, with most of the buildings completely empty.
